The correct comparison is princess F-VS2 ($2,141) vs emerald F-VS1 ($3,350): $1,209 gap for the same color, one clarity grade higher in emerald. The VS1 step-up in emerald is not optional — it is the minimum clarity grade that produces a reliably eye-clean emerald cut at 1ct.

**At 2ct — where the gap widens:**

Princess 2ct G-VS2 GIA prices at $12,229. Emerald 2ct reaches [E-VVS2 Ideal GIA at $25,480](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28817893?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). The gap at matched grade-equivalents approaches $10,000–$13,000. This is where emerald's mandatory quality floor — VS1 clarity plus E-F color at 2ct+ — creates a structural price gap that princess does not impose.

**Lab-grown option for emerald:** [IGI E-VVS1 1.54ct Excellent at $2,040](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28523264?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) delivers more carat weight than natural 1ct for less money. Lab-grown emerald cuts collapse the price gap significantly — a [GCAL D-IF 2.04ct Ideal at $4,260](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28785493?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is less than natural emerald entry at 1ct.

